<tr><td><font face="Comic Sans MS" size=2>This item was found at the <a href=http://www.eqvault.com/> EQVault</a> website and is of extreme importance:<br><br>&quot;I just wanted to shoot a warning out to those that might be considering, or are already in a transaction to purchase an Everquest account on Ebay. Currently, we have evidence that there are several individuals that are attempting to defraud legitimate bidders, and Everquest gamers out of large sums of money. &quot;On 09/06/99 we decided to partake in the auction of a Level 50 Cleric character. The bidding on this character was proceeding slowly, and it looked like we would win the bid at around $320.00. Suddenly, a new bidder entered the arena, and put in a single bid proxy bid at $800.00, up from $320.00. We attempted to outbid him, and were forced to enter a bid of $810.00 to finally win, as he didn't escalate it any further. <br>&quot;Normally, this would appear to be how competative bidding works. However, we investigated further, and spent many hours on Ebay researching closed auctions and the accounts of regulars that post or purchase Everquest accounts. We discovered that the aggressive bidder in the auction we just won purchased the very same account on 08/29/99 for $399.00. 6 Days later, someone new is selling the account, and the person that is driving the bids over $800.00 is the same person who purchased the account 6 days prior? Its called bid padding, its a fraud, and is a felony in some states, and is considered wire fraud in a select few states. It gets worse, the original seller on 08/29/99 was another one of the high bidders! The bidding was stuck at $100.00 for the account, and the original seller comes in and bids $399(amazingly) and begins the drive to rise the cost of the character, he never bids again after this initial boost. <br><br>&quot;Speculation leads us to believe that we have a <i>group of delinquent minors that are using Everquest and Ebay to defraud </i>many innocent people out of hard earned cash. We caution anyone that is considering purchasing an account to deal with only adults, and individuals with positive feedback, references and to very carefully research the Ebay databases for prior auctions. <br><br>&quot;Everquest accounts have been sold for up to $20,000 on Ebay. <i>Clearly, a vast majority of these auctions are padded, inflated, and simply fantasies of minors wishing big things. </i>We've seen people spend large amounts of money on frivalous things, but the facts are clear, most true, legitimate everquest accounts have a <b>real market value of between $100 and $600.00. </b>If you are paying much more than this, the likelyhood of the bids being padded is tremendous, the likelyhood of you being defrauded is extremely high. They are banking on the fact that at least one legitimate person wants the account, and will keep bidding on it against their &quot;Staged&quot; competitor/s, driving the price to high levels. We've seen accounts that they haven't played there con game on sell for $100-$300 for well geared level 50 characters. So the obvious plan of action they are using is to scoop up level 50 accounts at a low cost, then resell them a few days later, driving the price up with their con game partners. <br><br>&quot;Currently, the Attorney Generals office in my state is investigating the bid we were a part of, and the young man that attempted to defraud us.&quot; <br><br>- Robert<br><br><b>Caveat Emptor 9:50 AM </b><br><br>Due to the recent Ebay situation, it is necessary to remind our players of &quot;Caveat Emptor&quot; - Let The Buyer Beware. Unless otherwise noted, we at Verant do not imply any affiliation, legitimacy or trustworthiness of the hosts and vendors at the events listed in the News Sections or at online auctions. We are not responsible for event cancellations, loss of proceeds and merchandise, or misrepresentations. Use the same caution you would in any real world scenario, and attend these events and auctions at your own risk. <br><br><b>More on Ebay Frauds; Response</b><br><br>From SteeleRaid:<br>I'd also like to submit this to the &quot;ebay Frauds&quot;<br>I read in the paper recently that ebay was cracking down on this themselves by giving credit card numbers, addresses, the works to the feds. So if you are one of these &quot;padders&quot; better knock it off and quick, or you might find yourself sharing a jail cell with someone you wont like.<br><br>SteeleRaid Shadowwalker<br><br>Triune Alliance<br>Bertox server<br>Thanks for the news, Steele! <br><br>Thanks all for info!</font></td></tr>
<tr><td><font face="Comic Sans MS" size=2><font color=#800000><a name=47></a><b><br>More on Yield</b></font><font color=#006600 size=1> [ <a href=mailto:eq_trade@usa.net target=main><font color=#006600>ShadowMaster</font></a> at 06:22 CST ]</font></font></tr></td>
<tr><td><font face="Comic Sans MS" size=2>Brad McQuaid had the following to say on alt.games.everquest, in regard to the new Yield policy.<br><br><i>So 6 level 25 campers are taking a larger risk to get the special loot from a level 32 mob, than my solo level 36? I don't think so.<br><br>-Jim Williams</i><br><br>Both the group of level 25 players AND the level 36 player are fine going after a level 32 mob. They all get exp. The yield rule does not apply there. The yield rule only applies if the player doesn't receive experience from killing the mob he is trying to camp. <br><br>A level 38 still gets exp off of a level 32, so the Yield rule would not apply. <br><br>If you think about 'soloing' as gaining exp and therefore levels playing by yourself, then by definition you couldn't be subject to the Yield rule, so I don't think the Yield rule threatens solo'ing. (Unless 'soloing' really means to some people sitting on a spawn that is absolutely no challenge to you, farming it for items, and refusing to get out of the way of a legitimate group who wants to actually enjoy a dungeon that was made for them). <br><br>We are sticking up for solo players here, despite the fact that some people who post here think I'm out to get soloing :)<br><br>-Brad<br><br>Thanks Brad! <br></font></td></tr>
